Part 1: Data

Brief background of the BRFSS:

  • The Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS) is a collaborative project between all US states, participating US territories, and the CDC.
  • The project is an ongoing surveillance system designed to measure behavioral risk factors of non-institutional adults aged 18 years and older who are residing in the US.
  • It was initiated in the year 1984, and has 15 states collecting surveillance data on risk behaviors through monthly telephone interviews.
  • It has been recorded an increasing number of survey participating states - by 2001, 50 states were participating in the BRFSS.
  • Today, all 50 states collect data annually, with some states such as American Samoa, Federated States of Micronesia, and Palau collecting survey data once in every one to three months (limited point-in-time).

Data collected: Preventive health practices and risk behaviors linked to chronic diseases, injuries, and preventable infectious diseases affecting the adult population. For example, BRFSS 2013 assessed tobacco use, HIV/AIDS knowledge and prevention, exercise, immunization, health status, alcohol consumption, fruits and vegetables consumption, seatbelt use, and many more.

Data collection method: Landline telephone and cellular telephone based surveys.

  • Landline telephone survey: Interviewers collect data from a randomly selected adult in a household
  • Cellular telephone survey: Interviewers collect data from an adult who participates by using a cellular telephone and resides in a private residence or college housing

Population target: Non-institutionalised adult population aged 18 years or older who reside in the US.

My understanding of the data and methods by which the data were collected:

  1. Generalisability: Random sampling was used in the landline telephone based conducted surveys where one adult in a household is randomly selected from the other adults presumably in the same household too. Random sampling means that every sample in a population, in this case, every adult in a household, stands an equal chance of being selected from the sample pool. This implies that results may be generalized across the population. However, there is no information regarding the selection method of the households. Are households randomly selected? If they are, then results from the randomly selected adults from the randomly selected households may be generalized across the population on a state-wide level. If households are not randomly selected, and/or if there are high non-response rates, then the data collected may potentially be biased.

  2. Causality: This is an observational study, not an experimental study in which random assignments would have been involved. Thus, any relational-correlation does not imply causation.

Research quesion 1: Is there a relationship between sleeping adequacy and general health status amongst the adult population in the US?

Rationale behind RQ1: There is no particular reason why I chose these variables to investigate its relationship for. I thought it’d be interesting to see if people who are ‘healthy’ are also getting sufficient durations of sleep. Maybe the duration of one’s sleep contributes to one’s general health status. Or perhaps, the other way round.

Research quesion 2: Do people who perceive themselves as being treated differently compared to people of other races in their workplace, report experiencing depression and/or hopelessness?

Rationale behind RQ2: Although feelings of hopelessness and depression are not solely and may not even be contributed by poor (or better) treatments in workplaces, based on race, I am interested to see if there are discernible patterns of self reported feelings of mental illness/ stigma across different groups of people who perceived themselves as being treated better or worse than people of other races in their workplace.

Research quesion 3: What is the relationship between education levels and lifestyle patterns?

Rationale behind RQ3: I want to explore Numerical, continuous variables this time.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

I will now explore each research question - first, visually, then using simple summary statistics.

Research quesion 1: Is there a relationship between sleeping adequacy (variable name: sleptim1) and general health status (variable name: genhlth) amongst the adult population in the US?

Survey questions for the above variables:

  1. sleptim1: On average, how many hours of sleep do you get in a 24-hour period? Responses: 1 - 24; Don’t know; Missing
  2. genhlth: Would you say that in general, your health is Responses: Excellent; Very good; Good; Fair; Poor; Don’t know; Refused; Missing

First, I create a new dataframe only containing the necessary variables. I also keep the first column on state names.

sleep_genhlth <- sleep_genhlth %>% filter(!is.na(sleptim1) & !is.na(genhlth))

ggplot(sleep_genhlth, aes(x=genhlth, y=sleptim1)) + geom_boxplot() + ggtitle("Sleeping durations for people of different Health statuses") + xlab("General health status") + ylab("Sleeping time (Hours)")

All in all, there seems to be a lack of relationship between Sleep time and General health status - all box plots share many overlapping Sleep time values.

Research quesion 2: Do people who perceive themselves as being treated differently compared to people of other races in their workplace (variable name: rratwrk2), report experiencing depression and hopelessness (variable names: misdeprd and mishopls)?

Survey questions for the above variables:

  1. rratwrk2: Within the past 12 months at work, do you feel you were treated worse than, the same as, or better than people of other races? Responses: Worse than other races; Same as other races; Better than other races; Worse than some, better than others; Only encountered people of the same race; Don’t know; Refused; Missing
  2. misdeprd: During the past 30 days, about how often did you feel so depressed that nothing could cheer you up? Responses: All; Most; Some; A little; None; Don’t know; Refused; Missing
  3. mishopls: During the past 30 days, about how often did you feel hopeless that nothing could cheer you up? Responses: All; Most; Some; A little; None; Don’t know; Refused; Missing

Similar to before, I obtain a second dataframe containing the three variables of self-perceived workplace treatment, feelings of hopelessness, and depression.

Description of graph(s): Most survey respondents perceived that they were treated equally as people of other races. Similarly, most survey respondents reported no sense of hopelessness and depression at all throughout the past 30 days.

Next, I want to overlay these data on a single graph, to observe the spread of self-reported hopelessness and depression across the different groups of self-perceived workplace treatment.

Because I want to gauge how many of those within each group of self-perceived workplace treatment felt hopeless or depressed, as well as compare them across the different groups, I calculate percentages/ proportions of not-hopeless-hopeless and not-depressed-depressed within each group of self-perceived workplace treatment. If I merely use counts/ numbers of people, as opposed to proportions, I would be disregarding the fact there is a disproportionately larger number of respondents who perceived that they were treated the same as other races in their workplace. Using mere number counts disables me from making standardized comparisons across the different groups. This entire process involves a few steps:

#make tables and proportion tables 
table1 <- table(race_mentalhlth$rratwrk2, race_mentalhlth$mishopls)
proptable1 <- prop.table(table1, margin=1)

#convert table into a dataframe 
prop_race_hopeless <- as.data.frame.matrix(proptable1) 
prop_race_hopeless$Self_percp_of_race_treat_workplace <- rownames(prop_race_hopeless)

#modify dataframe into a long format
prop_race_hopeless <- melt(prop_race_hopeless,id.vars=c("Self_percp_of_race_treat_workplace"),value.name="proportion")%>%rename(Feeling_hopeless = variable)

Now, for the other variable:

#make tables and proportion tables 
table2 <- table(race_mentalhlth$rratwrk2, race_mentalhlth$misdeprd)
proptable2 <- prop.table(table2, margin=1)

#convert table into a dataframe 
prop_race_depressed <- as.data.frame.matrix(proptable2) 
prop_race_depressed$Self_percp_of_race_treat_workplace <-rownames(prop_race_depressed)

#modify dataframe into a long format
prop_race_depressed <- melt(prop_race_depressed,id.vars=c("Self_percp_of_race_treat_workplace"),value.name="proportion") %>% rename(Feeling_depressed = variable)

Next, I plot the box plots:

#box plot showing proportion of peoples' feelings of hopelessness (or not) based on their self-perception of being racially discriminated against (or not) in their workplace 
ggplot(prop_race_hopeless, aes(x=Self_percp_of_race_treat_workplace,y=proportion,fill=Feeling_hopeless)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Better","Only same race","Same","Worse","Better and worse")) + ggtitle("Relationship between self-perceptions of workplace treatment and feelings of hopelessness") + xlab("Self-perceived treatment in workplace compared to people of other races") + ylab("Proportion of people feeling varying degrees of hopelessness")
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

Description of graph(s):

A stark majority of people from each group of self-perceived workplace treatment did not feel hopeless at all throughout the past 30 days during which the survey was conducted then. Amongst people who perceived themselves as being treated better, some felt hopeless a little of the time, and some also felt hopeless most of the time. Amongst people who perceived themselves as being treated worse, some also felt hopeless some of the time and most of the time. In fact, those who perceived equal workplace treatment also felt hopeless - all the time, most of the time, some of the time, and little of the time (although at much smaller proportions).

It is difficult to draw any conclusions from this graph, as perhaps the sample size is too small (n=169) for the deducing of any results. However, taking into account these limitations, it seems like the feeling of hopelessness cannot be solely explained by workplace treatment, as regardless of whether people perceived that they were treated better, the same, or worse than others of other races, there are people from all groups who reported feeling hopeless.

#box plot showing proportion of peoples' feelings of depression (or not) based on their self-perception of being racially discriminated against (or not) in their workplace 
ggplot(prop_race_depressed, aes(x=Self_percp_of_race_treat_workplace, y=proportion, fill=Feeling_depressed)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + scale_x_discrete(labels=c("Better","Only same race","Same","Worse","Better and worse")) + ggtitle("Relationship between self-perceptions of workplace treatment and feelings of depression") + xlab("Self-perceived treatment in workplace compared to people of other races") + ylab("Proportion of people feeling varying degrees of depression")
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

Description of graph(s): Similar to the previous plot, a majority of people felt no depression at all throughout the past 30 days during which the survey was conducted then. Patterns of depression intensity/ spread are mostly, vaguely (at least from the outset), similar to patterns of hopelessness intensity/ spread too. The only obvious difference between both plots is that where amongst people who perceived themselves as being treated worse, there are those who also reported feeling depressed all the time, whereas none reported feeling hopeless all the time. All these observations seem to me pretty inconsequential at the moment.

All in all, in regards to answering research question 2 (Do people who perceive themselves as being treated differently compared to people of other races in their workplace, report experiencing depression and hopelessness?) - yes, people who perceived themselves as being treated better or worse also reported themselves as feeling hopeless and depressed (at varying degrees). However, feelings of hopelessness and depression are not only exclusive amongst people who felt as if they were treated differenly - people who perceived same treatment also felt hopeless and depressed (although at a smaller percentage as a whole). In short, feelings of hopelessness and depression do not seem to correlate with differing self-perceptions of workplace treatment.

  1. educa: What is the highest grade or year of school you completed? Responses: Never attended school or any kindergarden; Grades 1 through 8 (Elementary); Grades 9 through 11 (Some high school); Grade 12 or GED (High school graduate); College 1 year to 3 years (Some college); College 4 years or more (College graduate); Refused; Missing

Education levels are Factor variables, and the rest are Numerical variables (Integers). After removing all missing values, I am left with 74,101 cases. Before, it was 555,019.

When analysing and interpreting the values stored under each Numerical variable, it is imporant to note that the values are not what they mean - in terms answering the survey questions. Notice that most values are three-digits. This does not mean that respondents consumed 200+ soda drinks in any given day, week, or month.

As per BRFSS Data description, the digits are coded with different underlying meanings. The first digit indicates the number of times per day, per week, or per month. 1 as the first digit indicates per day, 2 indicates per week, and 3 indicates per month . This pattern is true for variable soda_pop.

For variable exercise, there are only two levels to the pattern. 1 as the first digit indicates per week and 2 indicates per month

#create a function to add an apostrophe between the first digit and the rest. 
#This is to distinguish the first digit code meant for indicating day, week, or 
#month, and the second and third combined for indicating count, as well as for easier
#separation later on. I want the function to also add an apostrophe after the 0 digit, 
#and add another 0 after the apostrophe. This is for format standardization. 
reformat <- function(x){x%>%str_replace_all("^([1,2,3])(\\d+)$","\\1'\\2")%>%str_replace_all("^(0)$","\\1'0")}

#apply the function to variables 
soda_pop_reformat <- reformat(edu_lifestyle$soda_pop)

exercise_reformat <- reformat(edu_lifestyle$exercise)

#add new column to df to incorporate the above reformatted values 
edu_lifestyle <- edu_lifestyle%>%mutate(soda_pop_reformat=soda_pop_reformat,exercise_reformat=exercise_reformat)

#separate digits into new variables of timeframe and count 
edu_lifestyle <- edu_lifestyle%>%separate(soda_pop_reformat,c("timeframe_soda","count_soda"))%>%separate(exercise_reformat,c("timeframe_exercise","count_exercise"))

#label numerically-coded values of timeframes as 'per day','per week', or 'per month'
edu_lifestyle <- mutate(edu_lifestyle,timeframe_soda=ifelse(timeframe_soda==0,"never",ifelse(timeframe_soda==1,"day",ifelse(timeframe_soda==2,"week",ifelse(timeframe_soda==3,"month","others")))),timeframe_exercise=ifelse(timeframe_exercise==1,"week",ifelse(timeframe_exercise==2,"month","others")))
  
#remove all first digit 0s under variable count 
edu_lifestyle <- edu_lifestyle%>%mutate(count_soda=str_replace_all(edu_lifestyle$count_soda,"^(0)([1-9]{1}$)", "\\2"),count_exercise=str_replace_all(edu_lifestyle$count_exercise,"^(0)([1-9]{1})$", "\\2"))

#remove original variables that have now become redundant since reformatting 
edu_lifestyle <- edu_lifestyle %>% select(-c(soda_pop,exercise))

I can use a histogram and/or qqplot to look at the degree of normal distributions of the data.

It remains difficult to ascertain from these graphs if there is a relationship between education levels and lifestyle patterns, in terms of frequencies of soda consumption and exercises done in a month.
